post_text:
2020-2021 FFS materials (applications, instructions, guidelines) are now available on our web site: www.attleboroschools.com on the Transportation page. Our Transportation Office will be open for FFS applications from 8 am to noon daily starting July 20, 2020. We will not accept FFS applications after August 14, 2020. Social Distancing and Masking Guidelines will be enforced should you come for office hours. Payment for the 2020-2021 school year will not be collected until November, 2020. A deadline of November 15th will be in place to maintain bus service for the year.

We want to note that State of MA guidelines for student transportation in the fall have not yet been developed. These may greatly impact and limit our ability to provide FFS access to our families. Once the State has announced transportation guidelines, there will be information published on the district web site indicating how the guidelines impact our FFS ability.

post_text: We are relieved to announce that the results of COVID-19 testing are NEGATIVE for the student who we learned on Friday had been placed in self quarantine pending the outcome. We are confident in this information as a positive result would be reported to the state and be visible to our local Health Department. Moving forward, we will communicate directly to the affected school communities regarding any future positive test results. It is still possible that individuals who had contracted COVID-19 were in our schools during their incubation period. However, we will not be tracking any further quarantines or pending test results as any attempt to do so would be flawed. Neither the District nor our Health Department has access to the necessary information as a universal and complete list does not exist. Positive test results will be the only reliable way to assess potential exposure. We are hopeful that the timing of our closure was early enough to prevent community spread through our schools.

Food Support for Students: We are working with Whitson’s to develop a lunch program for students experiencing food scarcity and food insecurity. post_text: The Attleboro Public Schools are open tomorrow, March 13. In consultation with local health officials, we continue to deem our schools to be a safe place for our students. There are currently no cases of COVID-19 in Attleboro. However, as we have all experienced this week, the situation is quite fluid and we will continue to monitor conditions and move swiftly when circumstances change. Everyone should begin planning for the increasingly likely outcome that we will eventually experience a prolonged cancellation of two or more weeks. We will communicate more to families tomorrow after consideration of new information expected in the morning.

The Asthma and Allergy Foundation of America, New England Chapter (AAFA New England), as part of their Speaker Series Program, is pleased to present “Supporting Children with Food Allergies,” a program by two experts in the field of food allergies and children. Both Dr. LeBovidge and Dr. Pistiner are members of the AAFA New England Medical Advisory Committee.

On Wednesday, February 26th at 7:00PM, members of the school community are invited to join the doctors at Newton-Wellesley Hospital’s Shipley Auditorium or via Facebook live, to hear this important topic that promotes understanding and positive strategies for supporting children with food allergies at school. Participants can RSVP for the program by filling out the Google form at https://forms.gle/7f96ACGpgoArrNr88.

The Attleboro High School Music Department is proud to announce that its annual Winter Concert will be held this year on Thursday, Dec. 19 at 7 PM in the Robert H. Bray Auditorium. Admission is free. Donations are accepted ($3 suggested). Performances will include the Concert Band, Jazz Ensemble, Select Choir and Mixed Chorus. The program will include a variety of selections including: This Christmas, Various Themes on “Fa-La-La”, Ocho Kandelikas, A Trumpeter’s Lullaby, Sleigh Ride and more!

If you wish further information or would like to contact the music department, please call 508-222-5150 x1181.

On Thursday, the Massachusetts State Legislature introduced the Student Opportunity Act which is intended to reassess the formula that Massachusetts uses to fund school districts, potentially adding $1.5 billion to the public education system over the next seven years. Superintendent Sawyer, along with his Massachusetts Association of School Superintendents colleagues, praise our local legislative delegation for their consistent support on this critical issue.

https://www.massupt.org/2019/09/20/massachusetts-superintendents-applaud-student-opportunity-act/

Dear AHS Community,

In the strongest sense of Blue Pride, I remain,

Tonight, we were honored to Spotlight a cross section of the outstanding Class of 2019 at School Committee! We are very grateful to the School Committee and Central Office administration for their support.
The Class of 2019 were accepted at: 195 post-secondary institutions. The Class of 2019 will be attending: 94 post-secondary institutions
The Class of 2019 received $14,536,890 in renewable merit scholarships from their institutions (self-reported)!
The Class of 2019 received $233,540 from scholarship night from Attleboro-area donors!
99.7% of this Senior Class will be positively placed in the Fall (post-secondary institutions; military; or gainfully employed).
#BluePrideLivesHere

Attleboro High School has partnered with Bridgewater State University to hold a number of panel discussions on school related criminal justice issues. Last week, they held their second panel discussion on mental health. Find out more in the DoubleACS Daily News!

ASEPAC 3rd annual Make A Difference Award

We are pleased to share all our nominees and recipients of the 2019 ASEPAC Make A Difference Award.

Please check your email today and tomorrow for information and details regarding the event from Julie Doxsey - juliemdoxsey@gmail.com.

Congratulations to all! We have so many great people in our community!
